Some hints and tips around Stack Exchange:

  • Use https://stackoverflow.com/search, click on "Advanced..." to show options
  • Search within your favorites: Enter infavorites:mine search_expression
  • Search within your posts related to a tag. For example: user:mine [C#] finds everything you have posted that is related to C#.
  • Run SQL queries against stack overflow posts: check this out to download an archive and http://data.stackexchange.com/ to run SQL queries against current stack exchange sites
  • Use keyboard tags, e.g. <kbd>Alt</kbd> appears as Alt
  • If necessary, add line breaks with <br/> *)
  • Syntax highlighting in your posts - Use a tag like:
    <!-- language-all: lang-cs -->
    For available tags, see: this link and that link (meta)
  • Version tags: Use them to mark pre-C#6: <!-- if version [lt 6.0] -->
  • To add runnable CSS/HTML/JavaScript code, use the code sample icon {} when editing your question rather than providing a JsFiddle link (but JsFiddle is good for testing).
    If you want to add runnable .NET code (C#, F# or VB.NET), you can create it in DotNetFiddle and add a link (please provide the code in SO too because the link might become unusable). For screenshots you can use the free tool http://www.screentogif.com/
  • Hide answers: use >!, like so (point with the mouse):
    What is the answer to the ultimate question?

    The answer is 42.

*) use <sup>/<sub> for superscript/subscript

Most programs are too complicated ï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ that is, more complex than they need to be to solve their problems efficiently. Why? Mostly itï¿½ï¿½ï¿½s because of bad design, but I will skip that issue here because itï¿½ï¿½ï¿½s a big one. But programs are often complicated at the microscopic level, and that is something I can address here.

  • Rule 1. You canï¿½ï¿½ï¿½t tell where a program is going to spend its time. Bottlenecks occur in surprising places, so donï¿½ï¿½ï¿½t try to second guess and put in a speed hack until youï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ve proven thatï¿½ï¿½ï¿½s where the bottleneck is.
  • Rule 2. Measure. Donï¿½ï¿½ï¿½t tune for speed until youï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ve measured, and even then donï¿½ï¿½ï¿½t unless one part of the code overwhelms the rest.
  • Rule 3. Fancy algorithms are slow when n is small, and n is usually small. Fancy algorithms have big constants. Until you know that n isdoes get big, use Rule 2 first.) For example, binary trees are always faster than splay trees for workaday problems.
  • Rule 4. Fancy algorithms are buggier than simple ones, and theyï¿½ï¿½ï¿½re much harder to implement. Use simple algorithms as well as simple data structures.
    The following data structures are a complete list for almost all practical programs: array, linked list, hash table, binary tree.
    Of course, you must also be prepared to collect these into compound data structures. For instance, a symbol table might be implemented as a hash table containing linked lists of arrays of characters.
  • Rule 5. Data dominates. If youï¿½ï¿½ï¿½ve chosen the right data structures and organized things well, the algorithms will almost always be self-evident. Data structures, not algorithms, are central to programming. (See Brooks p. 102.)
  • Rule 6. There is no Rule 6.

I am working on a research report about the technologies categorized as the real-time web. So far I've spoken with 45+ different companies building or leveraging real-time technologies like PubSubHubbub, XMPP, Twitter, etc. My co-workers at ReadWriteWeb and I also hosted an event on the topic in Mountain View, CA in October.

I am not a developer but I admire what cutting edge developers do. Our site attempts to translate some of that in news coverage for end users.

I think StackOverflow might be a good place to find developers interested in suggesting some technical questions that I could ask the companies I'm profiling as case studies in the report I'm writing. I'm writing the report primarily regarding things like obstacles faced, lessons learned and value propositions articulated regarding the use of real-time technologies.

I'm posting drafts of my write-ups here and asking StackOverflow users to suggest questions you'd like to see the answers to, questions that presumably will be more technical than what I've asked. If I use one of your questions in the report, I'll contact you here and send you a copy of the full report when it's done at no cost.

It was on a cold day of autumn that I started learning C++. I never felt quite the same afterward. Gone were the days of patching the loose threads of visual basic. Suddenly, I didn't feel like I was wearing the oven mitts of batch files syntax. Those days were great, men were real men, women real women and memory was allocated where it needed be.

Those memories were short lived. The almighty need for exchange of currencies demanded Java. Oh the horror. Why, oh, why does it take 30mb of RAM for the world to see my greetings. Grieving passed and days became bright again. At last, a standard library that works. I erected a field of SEP on the collectors of orphaned objects. Ideas flowed faster than ever before in this canvas dot java. An army of ants armed with readability spread out to assemble my creations.

Yet, a desire remained. Why could a few lines in a spread sheet outdo all the shining design patterns scattered across the tall towers of my architectures. Was there a better world out there? Where a few statements could remain simple and yet reach for the sky, free from the bounds of tables!

Thus, deduced was born. A small child at first. It spoke very few words and couldn't quite run quickly on his feet just yet. But he had the gift of potential. With nurturing and care, let there be no limits he won't overcome.
